comments.body:
@ekr comment about asymmetry is on point. It may be possible to implement a solution for client certs along the lines he describes (Cert Request still offers mixed algs, Client's Cert rejected if not PQC). So technically this is feasible.

However the solution becomes super complicated when we look at management of the commitment cache for client certs. The cache may need to be indexed by SAN, by full DN etc., depending on the specific deployment and exactly how the cert is used to authenticate the client. In many cases an attacker could forge a slightly different but equivalent client cert and bypass the cache. All in all, high complexity and low benefit - we should remove any claims re: client certs from the draft.

Detailed analysis [here](https://github.com/yaronf/pqc-continuity-poc/blob/main/docs/analysis-client-identity-cache-key.md).
